I21``(a) T4Establishment of Commission._KThere is established a commission to be known as the Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce (in this title referred to as the `Commission'). The Commission shall_

I22``(1) be composed of 19 members appointed in accordance with subsection (b), including the chairperson who shall be selected by the members of the Commission from among themselves; and

I22``(2) conduct its business in accordance with the provisions of this title.

I21``(b) T4Membership._

I22``(1) T4In general._KThe Commissioners shall serve for the life of the Commission. The membership of the Commission shall be as follows:

I23``(A) 3 representatives from the Federal Government, comprised of the Secretary of Commerce, the Secretary of the Treasury, and the United States Trade Representative (or their respective delegates).

I23``(B) 8 representatives from State and local governments (one such representative shall be from a State or local government that does not impose a sales tax and one representative shall be from a State that does not impose an income tax).

I23``(C) 8 representatives of the electronic commerce industry (including small business), telecommunications carriers, local retail businesses, and consumer groups, comprised of_

I24``(i) 5 individuals appointed by the Majority Leader of the Senate;

I24``(ii) 3 individuals appointed by the Minority Leader of the Senate;

I24``(iii) 5 individuals appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives; and

I24``(iv) 3 individuals appointed by the Minority Leader of the House of Representatives.

I22``(2) T4AppointmentsK._Appointments to the Commission shall be made not later than 45 days after the date of the enactment of this Act [Oct. 21, 1998]. The chairperson shall be selected not later than 60 days after the date of the enactment of this Act.

I22``(3) T4VacanciesK._Any vacancy in the Commission shall not affect its powers, but shall be filled in the same manner as the original appointment.

I21``(c) T4Acceptance of Gifts and GrantsK._The Commission may accept, use, and dispose of gifts or grants of services or property, both real and personal, for purposes of aiding or facilitating the work of the Commission. Gifts or grants not used at the expiration of the Commission shall be returned to the donor or grantor.

I21``(d) T4Other ResourcesK._The Commission shall have reasonable access to materials, resources, data, and other information from the Department of Justice, the Department of Commerce, the Department of State, the Department of the Treasury, and the Office of the United States Trade Representative. The Commission shall also have reasonable access to use the facilities of any such Department or Office for purposes of conducting meetings.

I21``(e) T4SunsetK._The Commission shall terminate 18 months after the date of the enactment of this Act [Oct. 21, 1998].

I21``(f) T4Rules of the CommissionK._

I22``(1) T4QuorumK._Nine members of the Commission shall constitute a quorum for conducting the business of the Commission.

I22``(2) T4MeetingsK._Any meetings held by the Commission shall be duly noticed at least 14 days in advance and shall be open to the public.

I22``(3) T4Opportunities to testifyK._The Commission shall provide opportunities for representatives of the general public, taxpayer groups, consumer groups, and State and local government officials to testify.

I22``(4) T4Additional rulesK._The Commission may adopt other rules as needed.

I21``(g) T4Duties of the CommissionK._

I22``(1) T4In generalK._The Commission shall conduct a thorough study of Federal, State and local, and international taxation and tariff treatment of transactions using the Internet and Internet access and other comparable intrastate, interstate or international sales activities.

I22``(2) T4Issues to be studiedK._The Commission may include in the study under subsection (a)_

I23``(A) an examination of_

I24``(i) barriers imposed in foreign markets on United States providers of property, goods, services, or information engaged in electronic commerce and on United States providers of telecommunications services; and

I24``(ii) how the imposition of such barriers will affect United States consumers, the competitiveness of United States citizens providing property, goods, services, or information in foreign markets, and the growth and maturing of the Internet;

I23``(B) an examination of the collection and administration of consumption taxes on electronic commerce in other countries and the United States, and the impact of such collection on the global economy, including an examination of the relationship between the collection and administration of such taxes when the transaction uses the Internet and when it does not;

I23``(C) an examination of the impact of the Internet and Internet access (particularly voice transmission) on the revenue base for taxes imposed under section 4251 of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 [26 U.S.C. 4251];

I23``(D) an examination of model State legislation that_

I24``(i) would provide uniform definitions of categories of property, goods, service, or information subject to or exempt from sales and use taxes; and

I24``(ii) would ensure that Internet access services, online services, and communications and transactions using the Internet, Internet access service, or online services would be treated in a tax and technologically neutral manner relative to other forms of remote sales;

I23``(E) an examination of the effects of taxation, including the absence of taxation, on all interstate sales transactions, including transactions using the Internet, on retail businesses and on State and local governments, which examination may include a review of the efforts of State and local governments to collect sales and use taxes owed on in-State purchases from out-of-State sellers; and

I23``(F) the examination of ways to simplify Federal and State and local taxes imposed on the provision of telecommunications services.

I22``(3) T4Effect on the communications act ofK 1934._Nothing in this section shall include an examination of any fees or charges imposed by the Federal Communications Commission or States related to_

I23``(A) obligations under the Communications Act of 1934 (47 U.S.C. 151 et seq.); or

I23``(B) the implementation of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 [Pub. L. 104ÿ09104, see Short Title of 1996 Amendment note set out under section 609 of this title] (or of amendments made by that Act).

I21``(h) T4National Tax Association Communications and Electronic Commerce Tax Project._KThe Commission shall, to the extent possible, ensure that its work does not undermine the efforts of the National Tax Association Communications and Electronic Commerce Tax Project.

