I18(B) Health care provider

I13The term ``health care provider'' means_

I14(i) post-secondary educational institutions offering health care instruction, teaching hospitals, and medical schools;

I14(ii) community health centers or health centers providing health care to migrants;

I14(iii) local health departments or agencies;

I14(iv) community mental health centers;

I14(v) not-for-profit hospitals;

I14(vi) rural health clinics; and

I14(vii) consortia of health care providers consisting of one or more entities described in clauses (i) through (vi).

I18(C) Public institutional telecommunications user

I13The term ``public institutional telecommunications user'' means an elementary or secondary school, a library, or a health care provider as those terms are defined in this paragraph.

I18(D) Minor

I13The term ``minor'' means any individual who has not attained the age of 17 years.

I18(E) Obscene

I13The term ``obscene'' has the meaning given such term in section 1460 of title 18.

I18(F) Child pornography

I13The term ``child pornography'' has the meaning given such term in section 2256 of title 18.

I18(G) Harmful to minors

I13The term ``harmful to minors'' means any picture, image, graphic image file, or other visual depiction that_

I14(i) taken as a whole and with respect to minors, appeals to a prurient interest in nudity, sex, or excretion;

I14(ii) depicts, describes, or represents, in a patently offensive way with respect to what is suitable for minors, an actual or simulated sexual act or sexual contact, actual or simulated normal or perverted sexual acts, or a lewd exhibition of the genitals; and

I14(iii) taken as a whole, lacks serious literary, artistic, political, or scientific value as to minors.

I18(H) Sexual act; sexual contact

I13The terms ``sexual act'' and ``sexual contact'' have the meanings given such terms in section 2246 of title 18.

I18(I) Technology protection measure

I13The term ``technology protection measure'' means a specific technology that blocks or filters Internet access to the material covered by a certification under paragraph (5) or (6) to which such certification relates.

I19(i) Consumer protection

I11The Commission and the States should ensure that universal service is available at rates that are just, reasonable, and affordable.

