I12(4) the transfer of which (from Federal Government use) will not result in costs to the Federal Government, or losses of services or benefits to the public, that are excessive in relation to the benefits to the public that may be provided by non-Federal licensees; and

I12(5) that are most likely to have the greatest potential for productive uses and public benefits under the 1934 Act [47 U.S.C. 151 et seq.] if allocated for non-Federal use.

I19(b) Minimum amount of spectrum recommended

I79(1) Initial reallocation report

I12In accordance with the provisions of this section, the Secretary shall recommend for reallocation in the initial report required by subsection (a) of this section, for use other than by Federal Government stations under section 305 of the 1934 Act (47 U.S.C. 305), bands of frequencies that in the aggregate span not less than 200 megahertz, that are located below 5 gigahertz, and that meet the criteria specified in paragraphs (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section. Such bands of frequencies shall include bands of frequencies, located below 3 gigahertz, that span in the aggregate not less than 100 megahertz.

I79(2) Mixed uses permitted to be counted

I12Bands of frequencies which a report of the Secretary under subsection (a) or (d)(1) of this section recommends be partially retained for use by Federal Government stations, but which are also recommended to be reallocated to be made available under the 1934 Act [47 U.S.C. 151 et seq.] for use by non-Federal stations, may be counted toward the minimum spectrum required by paragraph (1) or (3) of this subsection, except that_

I13(A) the bands of frequencies counted under this paragraph may not count toward more than one-half of the minimums required by paragraph (1) or (3) of this subsection;

I13(B) a band of frequencies may not be counted under this paragraph unless the assignments of the band to Federal Government stations under section 305 of the 1934 Act (47 U.S.C. 305) are limited by geographic area, by time, or by other means so as to guarantee that the potential use to be made by such Federal Government stations is substantially less (as measured by geographic area, time, or otherwise) than the potential use to be made by non-Federal stations; and

I13(C) the operational sharing permitted under this paragraph shall be subject to the interference regulations prescribed by the Commission pursuant to section 305(a) of the 1934 Act [47 U.S.C. 305(a)] and to coordination procedures that the Commission and the Secretary shall jointly establish and implement to ensure against harmful interference.

I79(3) Second reallocation report

I12In accordance with the provisions of this section, the Secretary shall recommend for reallocation in the second report required by subsection (a) of this section, for use other than by Federal Government stations under section 305 of the 1934 Act (47 U.S.C. 305), a band or bands of frequencies that_

I13(A) in the aggregate span not less than 12 megahertz;

I13(B) are located below 3 gigahertz; and

I13(C) meet the criteria specified in paragraphs (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section.

I19(c) Criteria for identification

I79(1) Needs of the Federal Government

I12In determining whether a band of frequencies meets the criteria specified in subsection (a)(2) of this section, the Secretary shall_

I13(A) consider whether the band of frequencies is used to provide a communications service that is or could be available from a commercial provider or other vendor;

I13(B) seek to promote_

I14(i) the maximum practicable reliance on commercially available substitutes;

I14(ii) the sharing of frequencies (as permitted under subsection (b)(2) of this section);

I14(iii) the development and use of new communications technologies; and

I14(iv) the use of nonradiating communications systems where practicable; and

