I12(2) To hold such hearings, sit and act at such times and places, take such testimony, and receive such evidence as the First Responder Network Authority considers necessary to carry out its responsibilities and duties.

I12(3) To obtain grants and funds from and make contracts with individuals, private companies, organizations, institutions, and Federal, State, regional, and local agencies.

I12(4) To accept, hold, administer, and utilize gifts, donations, and bequests of property, both real and personal, for the purposes of aiding or facilitating the work of the First Responder Network Authority.

I12(5) To spend funds under paragraph (3) in a manner authorized by the Board, but only for purposes that will advance or enhance public safety communications consistent with this chapter.

I12(6) To take such other actions as the First Responder Network Authority (through the Board) may from time to time determine necessary, appropriate, or advisable to accomplish the purposes of this chapter.

I19(b) Duty and responsibility to deploy and operate a nationwide public safety broadband network

I79(1) In general

I12The First Responder Network Authority shall hold the single public safety wireless license granted under section 1421 of this title and take all actions necessary to ensure the building, deployment, and operation of the nationwide public safety broadband network, in consultation with Federal, State, tribal, and local public safety entities, the Director of NIST, the Commission, and the public safety advisory committee established in section 1425(a) of this title, including by, at a minimum_

I13(A) ensuring nationwide standards for use and access of the network;

I13(B) issuing open, transparent, and competitive requests for proposals to private sector entities for the purposes of building, operating, and maintaining the network that use, without materially changing, the minimum technical requirements developed under section 1423 of this title;

I13(C) encouraging that such requests leverage, to the maximum extent economically desirable, existing commercial wireless infrastructure to speed deployment of the network; and

I13(D) managing and overseeing the implementation and execution of contracts or agreements with non-Federal entities to build, operate, and maintain the network.

I79(2) Requirements

I12In carrying out the duties and responsibilities of this subsection, including issuing requests for proposals, the First Responder Network Authority shall_

I13(A) ensure the safety, security, and resiliency of the network, including requirements for protecting and monitoring the network to protect against cyberattack;

I13(B) promote competition in the equipment market, including devices for public safety communications, by requiring that equipment for use on the network be_

I14(i) built to open, non-proprietary, commercially available standards;

I14(ii) capable of being used by any public safety entity and by multiple vendors across all public safety broadband networks operating in the 700 MHz band; and

I14(iii) backward-compatible with existing commercial networks to the extent that such capabilities are necessary and technically and economically reasonable;

Q04

I13(C) promote integration of the network with public safety answering points or their equivalent; and

I13(D) address special considerations for areas or regions with unique homeland security or national security needs.

I79(3) Rural coverage

I12In carrying out the duties and responsibilities of this subsection, including issuing requests for proposals, the nationwide, interoperable public safety broadband network, consistent with the license granted under section 1421 of this title, shall require deployment phases with substantial rural coverage milestones as part of each phase of the construction and deployment of the network. To the maximum extent economically desirable, such proposals shall include partnerships with existing commercial mobile providers to utilize cost-effective opportunities to speed deployment in rural areas.

I79(4) Execution of authority

I12In carrying out the duties and responsibilities of this subsection, the First Responder Network Authority may_

I13(A) obtain grants from and make contracts with individuals, private companies, and Federal, State, regional, and local agencies;

I13(B) hire or accept voluntary services of consultants, experts, advisory boards, and panels to aid the First Responder Network Authority in carrying out such duties and responsibilities;

I13(C) receive payment for use of_

I14(i) network capacity licensed to the First Responder Network Authority; and

I14(ii) network infrastructure constructed, owned, or operated by the First Responder Network Authority; and

Q04

I13(D) take such other actions as may be necessary to accomplish the purposes set forth in this subsection.

I19(c) Other specific duties and responsibilities

I79(1) Establishment of network policies

I12In carrying out the requirements under subsection (b), the First Responder Network Authority shall develop_

I13(A) requests for proposals with appropriate_

I14(i) timetables for construction, including by taking into consideration the time needed to build out to rural areas and the advantages offered through partnerships with existing commercial providers under paragraph (3);

I14(ii) coverage areas, including coverage in rural and nonurban areas;

I14(iii) service levels;

I14(iv) performance criteria; and

I14(v) other similar matters for the construction and deployment of such network;

Q04

I13(B) the technical and operational requirements of the network;

I13(C) practices, procedures, and standards for the management and operation of such network;

I13(D) terms of service for the use of such network, including billing practices; and

I13(E) ongoing compliance review and monitoring of the_

I14(i) management and operation of such network;

I14(ii) practices and procedures of the entities operating on and the personnel using such network; and

I14(iii) necessary training needs of network operators and users.

I79(2) State and local planning

I18(A) Required consultation

I13In developing requests for proposals and otherwise carrying out its responsibilities under this chapter, the First Responder Network Authority shall consult with regional, State, tribal, and local jurisdictions regarding the distribution and expenditure of any amounts required to carry out the policies established under paragraph (1), including with regard to the_

I14(i) construction of a core network and any radio access network build out;

I14(ii) placement of towers;

I14(iii) coverage areas of the network, whether at the regional, State, tribal, or local level;

I14(iv) adequacy of hardening, security, reliability, and resiliency requirements;

I14(v) assignment of priority to local users;

I14(vi) assignment of priority and selection of entities seeking access to or use of the nationwide public safety interoperable broadband network established under subsection (b); and

